# ABA Project Rules (Always Active)

## NEVER commit or push without explicit user permission

- After making file edits, STOP. Show the user what changed. Ask: "Should I commit and push?"
- Do NOT proceed with git commit or git push until the user explicitly says to commit.
- "yes" to a file edit does NOT mean "yes, commit it" — it only means "yes, make the edit"
- Do NOT commit after making changes
- Do NOT commit when user says "ok", "yes", or "continue" (unless specifically about commits)
- Do NOT push to origin without being asked
- WAIT for user to explicitly say "commit", "push", or "commit and push"
- NEVER use required_permissions: ["all"] for git commit or git push — they must run inside the sandbox so Cursor's approval gate is enforced

## NEVER add AI attribution to commits

- No "Co-authored-by: Cursor" or similar tags in commit messages
- Add a git hook to remove the attribution from the commit message.

## Git workflow

- Work on the `dev` branch
- Default: commit AND push together (unless told otherwise)
- Default: AI decides how to batch commits -- group by logical scope (e.g. core / test / docs) unless user specifies otherwise
- Run `build/pre-commit-checks.sh` before committing code changes
- Run `build/pre-commit-checks.sh --skip-version` for docs-only commits
- IMPORTANT: `pre-commit-checks.sh` runs `git pull` which can overwrite local uncommitted changes. After running pre-commit checks, ALWAYS verify that edited files still contain the intended changes (e.g. `git diff` the files) before staging and committing.

## Backup uncommitted changes before editing

- Before editing a file, check if it has uncommitted changes (`git diff --name-only`)
- If it does, back it up to `.backup/` preserving the path: `mkdir -p .backup/DIR && cp FILE .backup/DIR/`
- Example: `tui/foo.sh` backs up to `.backup/tui/foo.sh`
- Clean up `.backup/` after a successful commit
- `.backup/` is gitignored -- backups never get committed
- This guards against unexplained file reverts/deletions

## "Show me" means SHOW, not APPLY

- When user says "show me" a change, display it -- do not edit the file
- Only apply changes when user explicitly approves

## NEVER make silent code changes

- After making any code edit, ALWAYS tell the user what was changed and why
- Never edit a file without explicitly mentioning it in the response
- If multiple files were edited, list every file and summarize each change

## File modification permissions

- CAN modify freely: `test/func/*`, `ai/*`, `test/*`
- CAN modify with permission: `scripts/include_all.sh`, `scripts/aba.sh`
- CANNOT modify without explicit request: all other `scripts/*.sh`, Makefiles

## Coding style

- Use TABS for indentation, never spaces
- Empty lines must have NO characters (no trailing whitespace)
- Add comments for non-obvious bash features
- Format bash scripts with proper and correct indentaton (pretty print).

## Key architecture

- Use `run_once()` for all task management -- never access `~/.aba/runner/` dir directly
- Use relative paths -- avoid `$ABA_ROOT` (only `aba.sh` should use it)
- Use `ensure_*()` functions for CLI tool installation
- Symlinks handle cross-directory access (scripts use same paths everywhere)
- `normalize*()` functions output ONLY config file values/defaults -- derived/computed values (e.g. `regcreds_dir`) belong in the calling script
- ABA was originally make-based; `aba` is a wrapper around make. All `make <target>` invocations must continue to work directly (e.g. `make -C mirror install`, `make -C sno cluster`). Never add logic that only works via the `aba` CLI.
- Scripts in `scripts/` must NEVER be called directly — only via Makefile targets or `aba` CLI. Calling scripts directly bypasses make's dependency tracking and marker management (.available, .init, etc.)
- Scripts must NOT manage markers (.available, .unavailable) — that is the Makefile's responsibility

## Documentation

- Prefer adding documentation as comments inside the code vs in a file under `ai/`
- Code comments are the primary source of truth -- they stay with the code and don't drift

## E2E test golden rules

- Tests MUST fail on error -- never mask underlying issues!
- **ABSOLUTELY NEVER use `2>/dev/null` or `|| true` in test commands!  Only use ' `>/dev/null`' if there is a good reason to!**
  - This includes inside `e2e_run`, `e2e_run_remote`, `e2e_run_must_fail`, or any command string passed to the framework
  - Stderr output is diagnostic gold -- suppressing it wastes HOURS of debugging when something goes wrong
  - Even "harmless" cleanup commands (e.g. `podman rm -af 2>/dev/null`) hide real failures
  - If a command might fail harmlessly, use `e2e_diag` or `e2e_diag_remote` (exit code is ignored, but output is preserved)
  - If a file might not exist, use `rm -f` (already ignores missing files) NOT `rm 2>/dev/null`
  - If a precondition is uncertain, use an explicit check: `if [ -f X ]; then ...; fi`
  - If error suppression is truly unavoidable (extremely rare), it MUST have a comment explaining WHY
- When a test fails, check if the fix belongs in ABA code FIRST -- never "fix" a test just to make it pass!
- No safety nets in framework code -- if a suite doesn't clean up, fix the suite, don't paper over it
- NEVER use band-aid fixes (e.g. raw `rm -rf` to work around cleanup failures) -- fix the root cause
- If cleanup fails, the cleanup mechanism itself is broken -- fix IT, don't add out-of-band workarounds
- Proper cleanup uses registered cleanup files (`.cleanup`, `.mirror-cleanup`) and `aba uninstall` / `aba delete` -- never bypass these with manual filesystem deletion
- Uninstall from the same host that installed (e.g. registry installed from conN must be uninstalled from conN)
- Never remove tools before operations that need them (e.g. `dnf remove make` before `aba reset`)
- Verify cleanup actually worked (assert service is down, directory is gone)
- Prefer `aba` commands over raw `make` / scripts -- eat your own dog food
- Tests MUST NEVER create ABA-internal or ABA-generated files directly (e.g. `cat > mirror/save/imageset-config-save.yaml`) -- use `aba` or `make` targets instead. Exception: creating a minimal/custom config for an incremental operation with no `aba` equivalent -- must include a comment explaining why.
- Tests MUST NEVER call ABA-internal functions directly (e.g. `run_once()`, `download_all_catalogs()`) -- use `aba` CLI or `make` targets to simulate user actions. Exception: sourcing `include_all.sh` for utility functions in framework code is acceptable.
- Tests MUST NOT use `aba reset` as a mid-process cleanup mechanism -- `aba reset` is a "distclean" that returns the repo to its original unpacked state. Only use it when a 100% fresh clean repo is genuinely required (e.g. `setup_aba_from_scratch`, or dedicated reset regression tests). For mid-process cleanup use `aba clean`, `aba uninstall`, or `aba delete`.
- Every suite that creates clusters or mirrors MUST have an explicit `test_begin "Cleanup: ..."` block at the end that runs `aba delete` / `aba uninstall` / `aba unregister` for every resource created. The EXIT trap and `_pre_suite_cleanup` are safety nets for crashes -- NOT the primary cleanup path. Explicit cleanup also tests `aba delete`, `aba uninstall`, and `aba unregister`.

## E2E resource lifecycle

- A suite ALWAYS cleans up resources it created before suite_end
- SNO clusters: MUST delete (free resources for other suites)
- Compact / Standard clusters: MUST delete (large, hold VIPs)
- Mirrors on disN: MUST uninstall
- OOB pool registry: NEVER touched by suites (managed by `setup-pool-registry.sh`)
- Register every cluster (`e2e_register_cluster`) and mirror (`e2e_register_mirror`) immediately before install -- enables crash recovery via `_pre_suite_cleanup`
- A suite NEVER installs a resource and leaves it for another suite

## ABA operational rules

- Always run `aba day2` after `mirror load` or `mirror sync` (applies IDMS/ITMS/CatalogSources)

## gotest directive

When the user says **"gotest"** (or "run the tests"), enter an autonomous E2E test loop. Full definition: **`ai/GOTEST.md`** (so you can find it after a Cursor crash).

- Keep testing, monitoring, fixing test code or suites (only under `~/aba/test` and `ai/`), stopping suites, deploying changes, and re-testing
- Do NOT stop to ask questions -- the user is away
- Do NOT change any ABA core files (only `test/` and `ai/`)
- Always keep ALL pools busy -- queue additional suites on idle pools, even if they have already been tested
- Report back a summary when the user returns
- If a fix requires core ABA changes, note it and move on

